# Apparently we have 3 groups within group 3, we will remove some marks that seem to disrupt the mapping by joining the 3 groups

LG3_final<-drop_marker(LG3_ORD_all, c(92,168,200,405,221,72,235,322,319,356,313,131,184,64,25,228,179,386,237,413,105,3,372,231))
LG3_final <- map(LG3_final)
rf_graph_table(LG3_final)

# We can see the presence of 3 very distinct groups within group 3, so we will use the group function to separate them

Group3 <- group(LG3_final, LOD = LOD_sug)

We have a total of 16 groups

Looking at the map already published group 1 corresponds to 1 and 13 of our data set

In the published map group 14 corresponds to the union of groups 9 and 14 of our group.

However, when we ask for the formation of the groups without the marks removed for the break of group 3 (below), we have the formation of 16 groups, which are the original 14 + 2 originated from the break of group 3 (lod tested 5 8)

In this way we decided to add tags with segregation detours to increase the size of groups 13 and 14 so that they can be correctly attached to their link groups
